**Sec. 90001. Border infrastructure and wall system.**
The Commissioner of U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP) receives $46,550,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to construct, install, or improve primary, waterborne, and secondary barriers, access roads, and detection technology like cameras and sensors. These funds remain available until September 30, 2029, and cover necessary ground preparation work to enable CBP operations along the border. The appropriation is drawn from unappropriated Treasury funds to support these specific infrastructure elements without affecting other budget lines.

**Sec. 90002. U.S. Customs and Border Protection personnel, fleet vehicles, and facilities.**
CBP is appropriated $4,100,000,000 to hire and train additional agents and officers, $2,052,630,000 for recruitment and retention bonuses, $855,000,000 for patrol vehicle repairs and acquisitions, and $5,000,000,000 for facility construction and improvements, all available until September 30, 2029. A restriction prohibits using these funds to recruit or train personnel for processing coordinator duties after October 31, 2028. The total allocation targets the expansion of Border Patrol, Office of Field Operations, and Air and Marine units.

**Sec. 90003. Detention capacity.**
U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) receives $45,000,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to expand single adult alien and family residential center detention capacity, with funds available until September 30, 2029. Aliens may be detained at family residential centers pending removal decisions or until removal is executed, while detention standards for single adults are set at the discretion of the Secretary of Homeland Security. The section defines family residential centers as facilities for detaining family units, including children who are not classified as unaccompanied alien children.

**Sec. 90004. Border security, technology, and screening.**
CBP is allocated $6,168,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to procure nonintrusive inspection equipment, upgrade air and marine platforms, enhance surveillance technologies, and improve biometric entry and exit systems, remaining available until September 30, 2029. The funds specifically target combating illicit narcotics, including fentanyl, and conducting initial screenings of unaccompanied alien children. A restriction prohibits the deployment of untested surveillance towers on the southwest and northern borders that lack autonomous capabilities.

**Sec. 90005. State and local assistance.**
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) receives $500,000,000 for unmanned aircraft system detection, $625,000,000 for the 2026 FIFA World Cup, $1,000,000,000 for the 2028 Olympics, and $450,000,000 for the Operation Stonegarden Grant Program, all available until September 30, 2029. Additionally, a new $10,000,000,000 State Border Security Reinforcement Fund is established for grants to states and local governments for border wall construction, ground preparation, and alien relocation, available until September 30, 2034. States may apply for these funds for activities occurring on or after January 20, 2021, but cannot exercise federal immigration authorities.

**Sec. 90006. Presidential residence protection.**
FEMA is appropriated $300,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to reimburse state and local agencies for extraordinary law enforcement costs associated with protecting designated non-governmental residences of the President, with funds available until September 30, 2029. Reimbursements are limited to costs incurred on or after July 1, 2024, that are directly attributable to Secret Service protection requests and exceed typical operational costs. FEMA may use up to 3 percent of these funds for administrative purposes.

**Sec. 90007. Department of Homeland Security appropriations for border support.**
The Secretary of Homeland Security receives $10,000,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to reimburse costs incurred in support of the Department's border safeguarding mission, with funds remaining available until September 30, 2029. This appropriation is drawn from unappropriated Treasury funds to supplement existing resources for border security activities.

**Sec. 90101. FEHB improvements.**
The Office of Personnel Management (OPM) Director must implement regulations within one year to verify the eligibility of family members added to the Federal Employees Health Benefits (FEHB) program and conduct a comprehensive audit of family member coverage over a three-year period. The Director must also develop a process to disenroll ineligible individuals within 180 days and include a fraud risk assessment for ineligible enrollees in future reviews. Additionally, $66,000,000 is appropriated for fiscal year 2026 to fund these oversight and audit activities, remaining available until the end of fiscal year 2035.

**Sec. 90102. Pandemic Response Accountability Committee.**
The Pandemic Response Accountability Committee receives $88,000,000 for fiscal year 2026 to oversee the Coronavirus response and funds provided in this Act or other pandemic-related legislation, with funds available until expended. The definition of covered acts in the CARES Act is amended to include this reconciliation act, and the committee's oversight authority is extended from 2025 to 2034.

**Sec. 90103. Appropriation for the Office of Management and Budget.**
The Office of Management and Budget (OMB) is appropriated $100,000,000 for fiscal year 2025 to find budget and accounting efficiencies within the executive branch, with funds remaining available until September 30, 2029. This appropriation is drawn from unappropriated Treasury funds to support OMB's mission of improving federal financial management. [end of text]


